<h3>Starting late in a world</h3>

<p>If you join a world in a later phase, you should adapt your strategy. It is still important to build strong resource production first so your village develops quickly. You should also protect yourself from raids by neighbors. Upgrade your wall and hiding place, and recruit some units. A reasonable diplomatic message can also prevent annoying resource losses. Once you grow larger, you can raid resources yourself, which helps your village development significantly.</p>

<p>Now comes the biggest difference compared to a normal start:</p>

<p>Do not make the mistake of focusing everything only on nobles. It may seem logical because you want more villages to catch up, but it is often fatal. High-point players try to secure villages in your area to establish a strong strategic position. If you invest only in buildings and offense, you become an easy target and can lose everything with little resistance. Once attacks start, it is usually too late.</p>

<p>The main counter-strategy is strong defense, with many swordsmen and spearmen. You must not be an attractive, low-loss target for stronger players. If they suffer heavy losses at your village, they will usually leave you alone. Morale also helps here, reducing strong players' attacking power by up to 70%.</p>

<p>This security phase takes time, but it pays off because defensive troops remain useful throughout the game. Once you have a solid defense, for example at least 1200 spears and 1200 swords, you can begin building nobles and offensive troops.</p>

<p>You will likely notice from surrounding villages that the strategy was worth it.</p>

